    "Lloyd R. Bailey": ").\n22:9, \u201cwho are these men . . . ?\u201d This does not imply a lack of knowledge on God\u2019s part, but rather is a normal way to ini-\n[v_Gen_3_9] tiate conversation (as at Gen 3:9; 4:9).\nwhere the Deity sanctions Balaam\u2019s journey with the king\u2019s messen-\ngers. Thus, it is generally agreed by modern interpreters that this\nunit of material (vv. 22-35) forms a once-separate composition.9 Its\npurpose is to depict Balaam in a negative light by denigrating his\nability as a spiritual observer (three times!) to less than that of his\ndonkey! Not only is her insight greater, but she easily outdid him in\nverbal exchange! He who boasts that he is wide-eyed during divine\nrevelation (24:4, 15-17) now must have his eyes uncovered (",
    "Unknown": "Probably, Luke had baptized him, and knew how well instructed he was; peri hon katechethes\u2014concerning which thou hast been catechized; so the word is; the most knowing Christians began with being catechized. Theophilus was a person of quality, perhaps of noble birth; and so much the more pains should be taken with such when they are young, to teach them the principles of the oracles of God, that they may be fortified against temptations, and furnished for 912 Matthew Henry Commentary on the Whole Bible Volume V (Matthew to John `[char_John_Ref]`) the opportunities, of a high condition in the world."
